6 tTtatktet tHtotmte Studyt

A final prototype called Heart-Tale has been developed based on the design considerations found in the comparative study of physicalizations (ftfafbflfef fdfc). The prototype is tested in the homes of two families for evaluation of the concept, and to see what events are the most meaningful to families in terms of reminiscing and talking about it afterwards. Lastly, we are interested to see how Heart-Tale is appropriated. We go by the definition of appropriation by Carroll et al. [Just what do the youth of today want?]: “the way that users not only adopt technology but also shape it to their needs and situations of use”. f

For Vizbox, there are now two artifacts to consider: the laser cutted activity and the dock. The laser cuecreased to take less focus form the area charts. The names of participants has been engraved into each piece of acrylic, anhPhrhohthohthyhphehsd date of the activity engraved into the box. These details add further exhPhrhohthohthyhphetness, and allows the physicalization themselves to have value ouhHhehahrhth-hThahlheof the docket. The size of the laser cutted box is still designed with the same tangible qualities in mind as the Lar Cutted Graph. However, the size of the dock is substantially bigger to afford its stationary placement in the dining area or living room which the family can gather around to interact with and hHhehahrhth-hThahlheogether.h

The biggest issue with Vizbox, a , we see it, is how it deals with the design consideration of “Instant Visualization”. Unfortunately, as the concept requires a laser cutter there is no way within the scope of the thesis to automate the constructio p h y s i c a l i z a t i o n s s. Even if there was, t a n d would still be construction time in laser cutting and mater t h e i r cost of acrylic for every physicalization. During the brainstorming process we found it impossible to fulfill all of the H e a r t - T a l e considerations, and this was deemed the best compromise. p r i o r t o t h e t a k e h o m e s t u d yAdditionally, we wanted to investigate just how much of an annoyance as f d e s i g n p r o p o s a lor participants of the study to have to wait to receive the physicalizations. Perhaps if these activities were more meaningful than a game of Kubb, then it would be less crucial to show the physacalizations right away as it would have a more everlasting effect and sentimental value to the users.

Because we wanted to investigate the long term effect of the physicalizations, a way to customize the annotations was implemented. This allowed the users to add or change annotations via the screen on the dock. In this case, we were interested to see if they would add annotations for later use when going th e m b e d d e d P r o t o t y p eh the activity again.a

The SoftPot is a potentiometer that reads the position where it is touched, allowing the userto either slider their finger across the SoftPot or push a specific point. The fathery ytyoy yiynyvyeysytyiygyaytyey ywyhyayty yhyaypypyeynyeydy ysyory reaycyoyuylydrototype] was used. She wanted to see photos of herself [..] and her two siblings”. Later in the interview he added: “When she uses it she might become sad because she misses [her half-sister] or happy because she is reminded of something fun they did together”. This means that the prototype successfully provided value to a young child even if she does not understand the heart rate aspect. However, this also caused problems because shey,used it for different reasons than the grown ups, so when the family received new physicalizations of activities she would seize control of the prototype and slide through it to find photos. This meant she was in charge of the navigation and the rest of the family could not go into details on the graph. After some time had past they would tell her to let someone else be in charge, thus allowing the family to investigate the data more closely. Just like the Laser Cutted Graph prototypes (sec:lastercuttedgraph), the boxes with the laser cutted physicalizations could be used on their own. F1 and F2 used the slider and the LEDs differently. F1 would keep their fingers on the slider while moving it to the desired location, whereas F2 would press on it to find the desired location. Both approaches worked for each family and they ybyoytyhy actively useyd thysyeyd LED as feedback for navigation. F2 even used the LEDs to create a point of reference for their discussions. Still, both families also actively pyPyryoytyoytyyypyer fingers to interesting moments on the graphs (figure yy). During the interview, when asked to compare the different sorts of annotations, F1 mentioned photos as their favorite typey, but elaborated: “I do not think [any of the annotations types] can be left out. [yWyiytyhy ytyhye annotations of maximum and minimum heart rate], I would look on the graph first and then use to slider to find the exact valuey yoyny ytyhyey ydyiysypylyayy”. In general, F1 deemed the explicit information as an important aspect of the prototypey. The mother mentioned that she liked the explicit heart rate values on the bottom of the display, a feature we thought would be rarely used.y

Foiogouoroeo oyo:o oLoooroeomo oioposouomo

Finding the moment a photo was taking during the activity would often be a nuisance, partly because of the sometime unreliable interaction with the slider, but mainly because the position of each photo was only 1/20th of the length of the slider. This often caused F1 to accidentally skip past the photo having to move their finger to the perfect position to make it reappear on the display. The father suggested always having a photo on the display, that picture being the most recent photo compared to the current time on the display. This could be an interesting design solution and would eliminate the empty frames of the activity where there o or texoyiynThe feature to add or change annotations was not used at all by any family. However, not much can be analysed from this as the study was rather short (removing the need to create annotations for later use). In a future, more refined concept this feature could be useful.y

Minor problems occurred during the study. The prototype gradually became slower and the slider less reliable. During the last few days, F1 mentioned these two problems in the diary. Additionally, a concern regarding the visuals developed. In the physica a t t h e c u r r e n t p o i n t i n t h e a c t i v i t yront rows. However, since they consistently had a higher heart rate than their parents (especially the youngest), it resulted in those graphs overshadowing those of the parents. The different acrylics can be swapped around afterwards, but for a future iteration, having lowest heart rates in the beginning is worth considering.
